EA7foRwWJc5p6LkirehxxmUf3EXm55zM_sCv0P-Ttn5I9Mxda9EqR6keaVdB6MyL9okOZ5aeRVYMu0pqjmi7fk8H3NLjDOxoDu-1KRJ03dg-Bxn33eBIHdl0hqIcU2XOTt9tH0iVXl-ttW6EmD1qCxSqwP5KJRRhsf0UYpOqpFbjUr8yOL-KxallOq7eLzNgx9j_3YXiRaJNcsQu3hDcZDtajow6LWTnj3__Ogd0lrmGgKkh6nwUiHthactt4Qh62aDeXgp9A871CdqMWFH4O6E_Itx6BWN8u7tzKfs3I7yRfLUm6F-Bnxb9aJXZ_KoBodXofroIpnBeiqyCIkzAwhVfXWBI82jXm3FQ8GSWaUjJRsC4TX_YJve0CvaxvUsOMwvcGwQTzeswT9swWhlhzpx2y5DbElGLu071yTL7FYwVTph_HaYcvnb4ugwSdYsmerjPUoxHjDfwgr7Q9F5TJKUAivlPPp3ZpSa_BSyeBVpFrlatX9mWJLk23uy8mvxP8kFLJVNvs1B5q5kvOjhLaiaYjVNh7-bB3Dzf8lyHeCccDr3b9medbEITA7rZbJhJBZiXcR2s2QrgDWbx3sx3gtD3If0WNEswPiKaGAnrYu4GR7-CY3c0QKqW7ZLLRGQguxFBLkP5S6nA3snar67Q-e_4KCg-WwsC1oWyfZVDjGyQYlGChgqkbvqlGQbW4qsGuvZVGo4jWfusyINgEukcEDgzH_WZ1nfB8A32GcjluMgipe9fdJP-62RslBZa4oWjBIxRJ2pSP5lKp1u8lBV4OoZoqmMkOQHWk-F_TmIRUk_Squ1PNRGRb0iNdieYF9nGZEOwqxYuabvEhPI=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java test structure**\\n\\nI'm considering how to structure my Java test files to maintain a one-to-one mapping with coverage for each class. Adding a helper Java file could be a violation, so I'm thinking a better approach might be to keep it package-private within the same file. The existing tests often use package-private nested classes. To simplify things, I could move `UnsafeInjectionHarness` to a top-level package-private class at the end, which should help with compilation and checkstyle requirements.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Revising test class structure**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the structure of `HarnessDispatcher`, which is currently nested inside `UnsafeInjectionHarness`, extending a protected class. If JUnit doesn't scan the helper class, that might be fine. However, since the test class references the helper method, it could still be loaded during the build and analyzed. The native analysis may load the helper, but the superclass might not show up in the declared classes. I’m considering removing the nested block for `UnsafeInjectionHarness` from the public class and placing it outside. I also need to address `Accessor` and `DispatcherClassLoader`, which are currently nested.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Editing code structure**\\n\\nI need to compile the code and check for issues. I'm wondering about whether a potential JUnit test registrar can scan the method parameter, but I don't think that's the case here. It's important to confirm that I have the necessary imports included. Okay, I'll edit the code from `private static final class UnsafeInjectionHarness` all the way to the end to make sure everything is structured correctly. Let's get this looking right!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_cett6f5quIhAUG2cPCnROgDv|fc_016c67c62a44ff910169f808b5292c8191b8f42162efa93e6e", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.projectreactor.tools/blockhound/1.0.8.RELEASE/src/test/java/io_projectreactor_tools/blockhound/ClassInjectorInnerUsingReflectionInnerDispatcherInnerUsingUnsafeInjectionTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    private static final class UnsafeInjectionHarness extends ClassInjector.UsingReflection {\n        private UnsafeInjectionHarness(ClassLoader classLoader) {\n            super(classLoader);\n        }\n\n        private static void exerciseDispatcherMethods() throws Exception {\n            Accessor accessor = new Accessor();\n            Dispatcher dispatcher = new HarnessDispatcher(\n                    accessor,\n                    accessorMethod(\"findLoadedClass\", ClassLoader.class, String.class),\n                    accessorMethod(\"defineClass\", ClassLoader.class, String.class, byte[].class,\n                            int.class, int.class, ProtectionDomain.class),\n                    accessorMethod(\"getDefinedPackage\", ClassLoader.class, String.class),\n                    accessorMethod(\"getPackage\", ClassLoader.class, String.class),\n                    accessorMethod(\"definePackage\", ClassLoader.class, String.class, String.class,\n                            String.class, String.class, String.class, String.class, String.class, URL.class),\n                    accessorMethod(\"getClassLoadingLock\", ClassLoader.class, String.class)\n            ).initialize();\n\n            DispatcherClassLoader classLoader = new DispatcherClassLoader(\n                    ClassInjectorInnerUsingReflectionInnerDispatcherInnerUsingUnsafeInjectionTest.class\n                            .getClassLoader());\n            String packageName = PACKAGE_PREFIX + \"dispatcher\" + Long.toUnsignedString(java.lang.System.nanoTime());\n            String className = packageName + \".Injected\";\n            byte[] classFile = new ByteBuddy()\n                    .subclass(Object.class)\n                    .name(className)\n                    .make()\n                    .getBytes();\n\n            assertThat(dispatcher.getClassLoadingLock(classLoader, className)).isSameAs(classLoader);\n            assertThat(dispatcher.findClass(classLoader, className)).isNull();\n            assertThat(dispatcher.getDefinedPackage(classLoader, packageName)).isNull();\n\n            Package definedPackage = dispatcher.definePackage(\n                    classLoader, packageName, null, null, null, null, null, null, null);\n            assertThat(definedPackage.getName()).isEqualTo(packageName);\n            assertThat(dispatcher.getDefinedPackage(classLoader, packageName)).isSameAs(definedPackage);\n            assertThat(dispatcher.getPackage(classLoader, packageName)).isSameAs(definedPackage);\n\n            Class<?> definedClass = dispatcher.defineClass(classLoader, className, classFile, null);\n            assertThat(definedClass.getName()).isEqualTo(className);\n            assertThat(definedClass.getClassLoader()).isSameAs(classLoader);\n            assertThat(dispatcher.findClass(classLoader, className)).isSameAs(definedClass);\n        }\n\n        private static Method accessorMethod(String name, Class<?>... parameterTypes) throws